{
  "The hydrostatic pressure at depth h in a fluid of weight density w is:": "",
  "P = w / h": "",
  "P = w * h": "",
  "P = w * sqrt(h)": "",
  "P = w * h^2": "",
  "Hydrostatic pressure at depth h below the surface is P = w*h, where w is the weight density of the fluid (force per unit volume). For water, w = 62.4 lb/ft^3 or 9800 N/m^3.": "",
  "The hydrostatic force on a submerged horizontal plate of area A at depth h in water (weight density 62.4 lb/ft^3) is:": "",
  "62.4 * h * A": "",
  "62.4 * A / h": "",
  "62.4 * h": "",
  "62.4 * h^2 * A": "",
  "For a horizontal plate, the pressure is constant across the surface: P = 62.4*h. The force is F = P * A = 62.4*h*A. Integration is not needed because the depth is the same everywhere on a horizontal plate.": "",
  "Why is integration needed to find hydrostatic force on a vertical plate?": "",
  "Because the plate is curved": "",
  "Because the fluid is moving": "",
  "Because the plate has a non-uniform thickness": "",
  "Because the pressure varies with depth across the plate": "",
  "On a vertical plate, different horizontal strips are at different depths, so each strip experiences a different pressure. Integration sums the forces on all these infinitesimally thin horizontal strips to find the total hydrostatic force.": "",
  "A rectangular plate 4 ft wide is submerged vertically in water with its top edge at depth 2 ft and bottom edge at depth 6 ft. The hydrostatic force is (w = 62.4 lb/ft^3):": "",
  "62.4 * integral from 0 to 4 of h^2 dh": "",
  "62.4 * 4 * 4": "",
  "62.4 * integral from 2 to 6 of 4h dh": "",
  "62.4 * 4 * 6": "",
  "At depth h, the pressure is 62.4*h and the width is 4 ft. The force on a strip at depth h is 62.4*h*4*dh. Total force = 62.4 * integral from 2 to 6 of 4h dh = 249.6 * [h^2/2] from 2 to 6 = 249.6(18 - 2) = 249.6(16) = 3993.6 lb.": "",
  "What is the hydrostatic force on a rectangular plate 3 ft wide submerged vertically with its top edge at the water surface and its bottom edge at 5 ft depth?": "",
  "4680 lb": "",
  "936 lb": "",
  "2340 lb": "",
  "1170 lb": "",
  "F = 62.4 * integral from 0 to 5 of 3h dh = 62.4 * 3 * [h^2/2] from 0 to 5 = 187.2 * 12.5 = 2340 lb.": "",
  "A triangular plate with base 6 ft at the top and vertex pointing down is submerged so its top edge is at the surface. If the plate extends 4 ft down, the width at depth h is:": "",
  "6h": "",
  "6(1 - h/4)": "",
  "6 - h": "",
  "6h/4": "",
  "The triangle has base 6 ft at h = 0 (the top) and vertex at h = 4 (the bottom). By similar triangles, at depth h the width = 6(1 - h/4) = 6(4 - h)/4. At h = 0, width = 6; at h = 4, width = 0.": "",
  "The force on a semicircular plate of radius 3 ft submerged vertically with its diameter at the surface (curved part below) in water is set up as:": "",
  "62.4 * integral from 0 to 3 of 2*sqrt(9 - h^2) * h dh": "",
  "62.4 * integral from 0 to 3 of 3h dh": "",
  "62.4 * integral from -3 to 3 of sqrt(9 - x^2) dx": "",
  "62.4 * integral from 0 to 3 of pi*h dh": "",
  "For a semicircle of radius 3 with diameter at the surface, at depth h the horizontal width is 2*sqrt(9 - h^2) (from the circle equation x^2 + h^2 = 9). The force on a strip at depth h is 62.4 * h * 2*sqrt(9 - h^2) dh.": "",
  "If fluid density doubles, the hydrostatic force on a submerged plate:": "",
  "Quadruples": "",
  "Doubles": "",
  "Stays the same": "",
  "Halves": "",
  "Hydrostatic force is directly proportional to the weight density of the fluid: F = w * integral of h * L(h) dh. If w doubles, F doubles. The geometry of the plate and the depth distribution are unchanged.": "",
  "A square plate (side 2 m) is submerged vertically in oil (density 800 kg/m^3, g = 9.8 m/s^2) with its top edge at 1 m depth. The hydrostatic force is:": "",
  "9800 * integral from 0 to 2 of 2h dh": "",
  "800 * integral from 1 to 3 of 2h dh": "",
  "9800 * 0.8 * 2 * 4": "",
  "9800 * 0.8 * integral from 1 to 3 of 2h dh": "",
  "The weight density of the oil is rho*g = 800*9.8 = 7840 = 9800*0.8 N/m^3. The plate runs from depth h = 1 to h = 3 (top at 1 m, side length 2 m). Width is constant at 2 m. F = 7840 * integral from 1 to 3 of 2h dh.": "",
  "Pascal's principle states that pressure applied to a confined fluid:": "",
  "Is transmitted equally in all directions throughout the fluid": "",
  "Is proportional to the volume of the fluid": "",
  "Only acts downward": "",
  "Decreases with depth": "",
  "Pascal's principle states that a change in pressure applied to an enclosed fluid is transmitted undiminished to every portion of the fluid and the walls of the container. This is the basis for hydraulic systems.": "",
  "What is 'hydrostatic pressure'?": "",
  "The force of a fluid on a moving object": "",
  "Pressure caused by moving water": "",
  "Pressure exerted by a fluid at rest due to the weight of fluid above a given point": "",
  "The atmospheric pressure at sea level": "",
  "Hydrostatic pressure is the pressure exerted by a fluid at rest due to gravity. At a depth h below the surface, the hydrostatic pressure is P = rho*g*h (or P = w*h where w is weight density). It increases linearly with depth.": "",
  "What does 'hydrostatic force' mean?": "",
  "The force of flowing water on a dam": "",
  "The buoyant force on a floating object": "",
  "The total force exerted by a static fluid on a surface due to pressure": "",
  "The force needed to pump water": "",
  "Hydrostatic force is the total force that a fluid at rest exerts on a surface. It is found by integrating the pressure (which varies with depth) over the area of the surface: F = integral of P * dA.": "",
  "What does 'weight density' mean?": "",
  "Force per unit area": "",
  "Mass per unit area": "",
  "Mass per unit volume": "",
  "Weight (gravitational force) per unit volume": "",
  "Weight density (w) is the weight per unit volume of a substance. It equals mass density (rho) times gravitational acceleration (g): w = rho*g. For water, w is approximately 62.4 lb/ft^3 or 9800 N/m^3.": "",
  "What does 'fluid statics' mean?": "",
  "The study of fluids in motion": "",
  "The study of fluid evaporation": "",
  "The study of electrical charges in fluids": "",
  "The study of fluids at rest and the forces they exert": "",
  "Fluid statics (or hydrostatics) is the branch of physics that studies fluids at rest. It deals with the conditions under which fluids are in equilibrium and the forces they exert on surfaces. Key concepts include hydrostatic pressure and buoyancy.": "",
  "What is 'pressure' in physics?": "",
  "Force per unit volume": "",
  "Energy per unit area": "",
  "Pressure is defined as force per unit area: P = F/A. Its SI unit is the pascal (Pa), where 1 Pa = 1 N/m^2. In fluid mechanics, pressure at a point acts equally in all directions.": "",
  "What is the 'centroid' of a submerged plate and why is it relevant to fluid force?": "",
  "The point of zero pressure on the plate": "",
  "The deepest point on the plate; force is maximum there": "",
  "The center of buoyancy of the plate": "",
  "The geometric center of the plate; the force equals pressure at the centroid times the area": "",
  "The centroid is the geometric center of the plate. For a flat plate submerged in a fluid, the total hydrostatic force equals the pressure at the centroid multiplied by the plate's area: F = (w * h_centroid) * A. This is a useful shortcut for uniform-density fluids.": "",
  "What does 'gauge pressure' mean?": "",
  "The total pressure including atmospheric pressure": "",
  "The minimum pressure in a fluid": "",
  "The pressure above atmospheric pressure, equal to the hydrostatic pressure alone": "",
  "Pressure measured using a gauge device": "",
  "Gauge pressure is the pressure relative to atmospheric pressure. It equals the absolute pressure minus atmospheric pressure. In hydrostatic problems, P_gauge = rho*g*h, which is just the pressure due to the fluid column above the point.": "",
  "What does 'Archimedes' principle' state?": "",
  "An object in a fluid experiences an upward buoyant force equal to the weight of the fluid it displaces": "",
  "Pressure at a given depth is equal in all directions": "",
  "Fluid flows from high pressure to low pressure": "",
  "Heavier objects always sink": "",
  "Archimedes' principle states that a body wholly or partially submerged in a fluid experiences an upward buoyant force equal to the weight of the fluid displaced. This principle can be derived using integration of hydrostatic pressure over the body's surface.": "",
  "What is a 'pascal' as a unit of pressure?": "",
  "1 newton per square meter": "",
  "1 joule per cubic meter": "",
  "1 newton per cubic meter": "",
  "1 kilogram per square meter": "",
  "A pascal (Pa) is the SI unit of pressure, defined as one newton per square meter (1 Pa = 1 N/m^2). Standard atmospheric pressure is approximately 101,325 Pa.": "",
  "What does it mean for pressure to be 'isotropic' in a fluid at rest?": "",
  "Pressure is zero at the surface": "",
  "Pressure varies depending on the shape of the container": "",
  "Pressure only acts downward": "",
  "At any given point in the fluid, the pressure is the same in all directions": "",
  "Isotropic pressure means that at any point in a fluid at rest, the pressure has the same value in every direction. A fluid pushes equally in all directions at a given depth. This is a fundamental property of fluids in static equilibrium.": "",
  "A rectangular swimming pool is 10 m long, 4 m wide, and 3 m deep. What is the hydrostatic force on one of the 10 m by 3 m walls? (Use water weight density = 9800 N/m^3.)": "",
  "294,000 N": "",
  "441,000 N": "",
  "147,000 N": "",
  "882,000 N": "",
  "F = 9800 * integral from 0 to 3 of 10*h dh = 98,000 * [h^2/2] from 0 to 3 = 98,000 * 4.5 = 441,000 N.": "",
  "A dam has a trapezoidal face: 100 m wide at the top (water surface), 60 m wide at the bottom, and 20 m deep. What integral gives the hydrostatic force on the dam face? (w = 9800 N/m^3)": "",
  "9800 * integral from 0 to 20 of 100*h dh": "",
  "9800 * integral from 0 to 20 of (60 + 2h) * h dh": "",
  "9800 * integral from 0 to 20 of (100 - 2h) * h dh": "",
  "9800 * integral from 0 to 20 of 60*h dh": "",
  "At depth h, the width of the trapezoid decreases linearly from 100 (at h=0) to 60 (at h=20). Width = 100 - (100-60)/20 * h = 100 - 2h. The force integral is 9800 * integral from 0 to 20 of (100 - 2h)*h dh.": "",
  "An aquarium has a circular viewing window of radius 1 m, with its center at a depth of 3 m below the water surface. The total hydrostatic force on the window is:": "",
  "9800 * 3 * 2*pi*1 N": "",
  "9800 * 3 * pi * 1^2 N": "",
  "9800 * pi * 1^2 N": "",
  "9800 * 4 * pi * 1^2 N": "",
  "For a flat plate, F = (pressure at centroid) * area = (9800 * 3) * (pi * 1^2) = 29,400*pi N. The centroid of the circle is at its center, which is at depth 3 m.": "",
  "A triangular gate in a dam has its vertex at the water surface and base of 8 ft at a depth of 6 ft. What is the hydrostatic force on the gate? (w = 62.4 lb/ft^3)": "",
  "2995.2 lb": "",
  "8985.6 lb": "",
  "5990.4 lb": "",
  "4492.8 lb": "",
  "The width at depth h is (8/6)*h = 4h/3 (by similar triangles, 0 at vertex/surface, 8 at depth 6). F = 62.4 * integral from 0 to 6 of h*(4h/3) dh = 62.4*(4/3) * integral from 0 to 6 of h^2 dh = 83.2 * [h^3/3] from 0 to 6 = 83.2 * 72 = 5990.4 lb.": "",
  "A vertical plate in the shape of a semicircle of radius 2 m is submerged in oil (weight density 7840 N/m^3) with its diameter at the surface. What is the hydrostatic force on the plate?": "",
  "7840 * integral from 0 to 2 of 4h dh N": "",
  "7840 * integral from 0 to 2 of 2h*sqrt(4 - h^2) dh N": "",
  "7840 * integral from 0 to 2 of pi*h dh N": "",
  "7840 * 2 * pi N": "",
  "At depth h, the width of the semicircle is 2*sqrt(r^2 - h^2) = 2*sqrt(4 - h^2). The force = 7840 * integral from 0 to 2 of h * 2*sqrt(4 - h^2) dh. Using substitution u = 4 - h^2, this integral evaluates to 7840*(2/3)(4)^(3/2) = 7840*16/3.": "",
  "A submarine's circular porthole has a diameter of 0.5 m and its center is 200 m below the ocean surface. If seawater has weight density 10,050 N/m^3, what is the hydrostatic force on the porthole?": "",
  "Approximately 197,300 N": "",
  "Approximately 789,200 N": "",
  "Approximately 98,650 N": "",
  "Approximately 394,600 N": "",
  "F = pressure at centroid * area = (10,050 * 200) * (pi * 0.25^2) = 2,010,000 * pi * 0.0625 = 2,010,000 * 0.19635 = 394,600 N (approximately). The centroid is at the center of the circle, 200 m deep.": "",
  "A water trough has a semicircular cross-section with radius 1 ft. When filled to the top, what is the hydrostatic force on one flat end? (w = 62.4 lb/ft^3)": "",
  "83.2 lb": "",
  "62.4 lb": "",
  "31.2 lb": "",
  "41.6 lb": "",
  "With diameter at the top (surface), at depth h, the width is 2*sqrt(1 - h^2). F = 62.4 * integral from 0 to 1 of h * 2*sqrt(1 - h^2) dh. Let u = 1 - h^2, du = -2h dh. F = 62.4 * integral from 1 to 0 of -sqrt(u) du = 62.4 * [2u^(3/2)/3] from 0 to 1 = 62.4 * 2/3 = 41.6 lb.": "",
  "A tank shaped like an inverted triangle (vertex at bottom) is 6 m wide at the top and 4 m deep. It is filled with a chemical solution of weight density 12,000 N/m^3. What is the force on one triangular end?": "",
  "128,000 N": "",
  "64,000 N": "",
  "192,000 N": "",
  "96,000 N": "",
  "At depth h from the surface, the width = 6(1 - h/4) = 6(4-h)/4 = 3(4-h)/2. F = 12,000 * integral from 0 to 4 of h * 3(4-h)/2 dh = 18,000 * integral from 0 to 4 of (4h - h^2) dh = 18,000 * [2h^2 - h^3/3] from 0 to 4 = 18,000 * (32 - 64/3) = 18,000 * (96/3 - 64/3) = 18,000 * 32/3 = 192,000 N. Let me recheck: 18000*(32/3) = 192,000. Hmm -- checking the width function: top is h=0, width=6. Bottom is h=4, width=0. So width = 6*(4-h)/4 = 3(4-h)/2. F = 12000 * integral of h*(3(4-h)/2) dh = 12000*(3/2)*integral of (4h-h^2)dh from 0 to 4 = 18000*[2h^2 - h^3/3] from 0 to 4 = 18000*(32-64/3) = 18000*(32/3) = 192,000 N. So the answer is 192,000 N. But that matches option C. Let me verify: F = 12000*integral from 0 to 4 of h * (3(4-h)/2) dh. The coefficient is 12000*3/2 = 18000. Integral of (4h-h^2) from 0 to 4 = [2h^2-h^3/3] from 0 to 4 = 32-64/3 = (96-64)/3 = 32/3. So F = 18000*(32/3) = 192,000 N. The correct answer should be 192,000.": "",
  "An oil storage tank has a rectangular inspection hatch 0.5 m wide and 0.8 m tall on its side. The top of the hatch is 2 m below the oil surface (oil weight density = 8500 N/m^3). What is the force on the hatch?": "",
  "4,080 N": "",
  "6,800 N": "",
  "8,160 N": "",
  "10,200 N": "",
  "F = 8500 * integral from 2 to 2.8 of 0.5*h dh = 4250 * [h^2/2] from 2 to 2.8 = 4250 * (3.92 - 2) = 4250 * 1.92 = 8,160 N. Alternatively, F = pressure at centroid * area = 8500 * 2.4 * (0.5 * 0.8) = 8500 * 2.4 * 0.4 = 8,160 N.": "",
  "A flood barrier must withstand hydrostatic force from water 5 m deep. The barrier is 20 m wide. If the safety specification requires it to hold 3 times the calculated hydrostatic force, what force must the barrier be designed to withstand? (w = 9800 N/m^3)": "",
  "7,350,000 N": "",
  "4,900,000 N": "",
  "2,450,000 N": "",
  "14,700,000 N": "",
  "F = 9800 * integral from 0 to 5 of 20*h dh = 196,000 * [h^2/2] from 0 to 5 = 196,000 * 12.5 = 2,450,000 N. With the 3x safety factor, the barrier must withstand 3 * 2,450,000 = 7,350,000 N.": ""
